As Anonymous wrote to Dr. Math
On 08/25/2004 at 02:52:40 (Eastern Time),
>[Question]
>There are 100 coins divided into 10 stacks, with 10 coins in each 
>stack. There are 90 genuine coins and 10 fake. A genuine coin weighs 
>2 grams and a fake coin weighs 1 gram. The 10 fake coins are 
>contained in one of the stacks.
>
>You have a scale which can be used to weigh and number of coins. 
What 
>is the minimum number of weighings needed to find the fake coins? 
>Describe how you work out which stack contains the fake coins.
>
>[Difficulty]
>I'm not sure how you can tell whether it is inthe last three.
>
>[Thoughts]
>You can take two stacks and put them together, see which one is 
>heavier and the other one is the fack coins, if they are the same do 
>the same thing until you find the fake coins. 

Here is a hint. Be sure to use the full capability of the scale. This 
scale doesn't just compare two stacks and tell you which is heavier; 
it actually tells you how much one pile of coins weighs. You know how 
much each coin (genuine or fake) weighs. How can you use this 
information?

